I often wonder if millennials might be the last generation that can appreciate art purely and establish connections with artists without the pressure of having to view everything through critical, judgmental eyes.
We grew up in an era of media abundance when people shared a common understanding of popular culture, and now that sense of collective consciousness has disappeared.
Back then, we could immerse ourselves in content without considering its source, as tracing origins was not an easy task in that era.
We worship these artists like gods and have no reason to question this admiration. Consequently, we establish a kind of "sociogenic relationship" with them and regard it as an indispensable part of our lives.
This also explains why we are so enchanted with nostalgia.
While the show "The Office" was airing, my friends and I would gather together every Thursday to watch it while eating pizza.
This is entirely different from the experience of watching shows through streaming platforms now. Streaming platforms typically release 12 episodes at once, allowing everyone to watch at their own pace and post about the plot on social media with a "spoiler alert," or choose to discuss only within specific groups.
Subconsciously, we all yearn for a sense of collective belonging that connects us all.
It is precisely because of this nostalgia that we keep replaying TV shows like "The Office" or movies like "Broadcast News," and the unforgettable lines from these works spread widely online, much like memes.
We will quote from the classic lines in these works and believe that most people will catch the references.
Now, just because something goes viral on the internet, we cannot assume that everyone has seen it.
With information exploding, there are simply too many things we need to pay attention to, making it impossible to simplify... Do we still have the chance to escape this state of information overload?
Time and again, we discover new media, new artists, only to find that they turn out to be either notorious sexual predators or stubborn bigots steeped in偏见, a cycle that is endlessly frustrating.
On one hand, we indulge in nostalgia, and on the other hand, we are forced to acknowledge that the creators of the art we adore might have serious moral flaws. This contradictory mindset leaves us at a loss.
We will establish "sociomorphic relations" with artists even more carefully.
We gradually realized that it is difficult for someone who wants to acquire wealth and power to avoid hurting or exploiting others.
Because the collective consciousness of the media no longer exists, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, there are also some people who remain痴迷未悟, determined to elevate others to a godlike status, only to feign shock and dismay when their idols fall.
We are living in a time of transformation, and I can't help but wonder where we are headed.
